---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import globalCss from '../../styles/global.css?raw';

// The paste is sliced out of the site's own global.css — one source of truth.
const START = '@custom-variant dark';
const END = '/* ============== end of the token paste ==============';
const startIndex = globalCss.indexOf(START);
const endIndex = globalCss.indexOf(END);
if (startIndex === -1 || endIndex === -1)
  throw new Error('installation: token paste markers not found in global.css');
const tokensPaste = `@import "tailwindcss";\n\n${globalCss.slice(startIndex, endIndex).trimEnd()}\n`;

---

<DocsLayout title="Installation — unscripted/ui">
  <article>
    <header class="mb-2">
      <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Installation</h1>
      <p class="mt-1.5 max-w-[60ch] text-muted-foreground">
        There is nothing to install, no package, no provider, no registry command. The
        components snippets is all you need.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="docs-prose">
      <h2 id="1-have-tailwind-css-v4">1. Have Tailwind CSS v4</h2>
      <p>
        Components are styled with Tailwind utility classes, including the newer variants
        (<code>starting:</code>, <code>transition-discrete</code>, <code>details-content:</code>).
        Any Tailwind v4.1+ setup works (Vite plugin, PostCSS, or the CLI).
      </p>

      <h2 id="2-copy-the-shadcns-tokens-optional">2. Copy the shadcn's tokens (optional)</h2>
      <p>
        These are the shadcn variables mapped to Tailwind v4's <code>@theme</code>. If your
        project already uses shadcn/ui, you already have these variables so you can skip most of this and keep your theme.
        The components should match it automatically.
      </p>
      <p>
        The paste also carries the global <code>prefers-reduced-motion</code> rule the components rely on. Anything else a
        component needs (like the accordion's <code>interpolate-size</code>) travels inline
        in its own markup. The <code>dark</code> variant is class-driven: add <code>.dark</code> to <code>&lt;html&gt;</code> however you like.
      </p>
      <CodeBlock code={tokensPaste} lang="css" />

      <h2 id="3-copy-components">3. Copy components</h2>
      <p>
        Every component page has a Preview/Code switcher (itself built with this library's
        radio-tabs technique 😉). Copy the HTML, paste it, modify as needed, done. Exactly two components
        (<a href="/components/carousel">Carousel</a> and <a href="/components/marquee">Marquee</a>)
        ship an extra CSS block, and their pages explain why.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</DocsLayout>
